name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (35/36) I‚Äôve never been more hopeful and optimistic about the future of our state. Let‚Äôs work with courage to unite, inspire & lead with hope. May God bless the state of Arkansas and give us courage to keep America strong, united, and free.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (34/36) Leaders can appeal to the instincts of fear, or they can lead with hope. In today‚Äôs world and, yes, in Arkansas, let‚Äôs join together to bring out the best of our fellow citizens.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (33/36) These moments in history remind us that leaders make a difference and that we can do more and earn the respect of the world when we are united and when we are following the better angels of the American spirit.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (32/36) I witnessed Neil Armstrong land on the moon to win the space race, and I saw the fall of the Berlin wall. I observed from a very personal standpoint how we all came together as a nation after the 9-11 attack.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (31/36) If you simply concentrated on those tragic moments in our history, then you might be discouraged about America. But I also remember and lived through the Berlin airlift; the Cuban Missile Crisis when our leaders stood tall against a Soviet threat.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (30/36) And our nation is blessed as well. I think back in my lifetime, and I can recall the division and protests of the Vietnam War, the turmoil of Watergate, the assassinations of Presidents and civil rights leaders, and the bitter political fights in Washington.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (29/36) As to the state of our state, I am grateful to say that Arkansas is leading. We are leading in computer science education, technology innovation, agriculture, tourism, job creation & support for veterans & law enforcement. We have more to do, but our state is blessed.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (28/36) Currently, we have a record back-up of state prisoners in our county jails. This limits the counties & cities in their capacity to enforce laws. This backlog must be remedied & for that reason I recommend a one-time investment to fund a new 498 inmate prison facility.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (27/36) The troopers not only patrol the highways, but their SWAT units are regularly deployed in crisis situations across the state. They back up local law enforcement in the response and investigation of violent crime. I am very proud of their dedication and professionalism.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (26/36) As part of this effort, our budget will significantly increase the pay of our state troopers. Col. Bill Bryant has been a star in leading the State Police & the troopers are deserving of a more competitive salary.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (25/36) Currently, our law enforcement is underfunded, underpaid, and underappreciated. The actions of this General Assembly to fund more, pay more, and to appreciate more will send the unmistakable message that in Arkansas, we support and value our law enforcement partners.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (24/36) We have about $5 million in equipment requests from cities and counties but insufficient funds to cover those grant requests. I recommend $10 million of one-time funding from our June 30 surplus to adequately fund this grant program.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (23/36) Next, you passed Act 786 of 2021 to create the Public Safety Equipment Grant Program. The grant program has received applications for funding to purchase everything from body cameras to bullet proof vests.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (22/36) It is designed to reward and incentivize those dedicated officers who keep our streets safe and our homes protected.  The total cost of this initiative in support of law enforcement will be approximately $45 million.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (21/36) Because of your advocacy and hard work, I am able to announce support for the $5,000 one-time payment to every county and city certified law enforcement officer. This will be a one-time payment from our surplus effective June 30 when the fiscal year ends.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (20/36) The budget before you includes increased funding for education, health care & public safety. It includes stable funding for the victims of crime through the Crime Victims Reparations program. It provides funding for child abduction response teams & for 2 new drug courts.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (19/36) The businesses that drive these innovations in mobility will be leaders in the future economy. I want these companies to find a home in Arkansas and for our state to be a leader in future mobility.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (17/36) You will have choices to make. You will have the opportunity to remove regulatory burdens & pass legislation to advance new modes of transportation that will keep Arkansas in the lead.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (16/36) The Advisory Council will be charged with identifying state laws and regulations that create a barrier to the development and enhancement of electrification, autonomous vehicles, drone delivery and advanced air mobility in Arkansas.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (15/36) As governor, I won‚Äôt be here for the end of the story, but together we can write the first chapter. Today, I am announcing the creation of the Arkansas Council on Future Mobility.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (14/36) In order for us to lead, we need to have electric charging stations across the state.  Arkansas is scheduled to receive $54 million over the next 5 years from the federal government for electric charging station infrastructure.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (13/36) In Eastern Arkansas we produce the steel that is required for the battery casing in electric vehicles. So, we are in good position to shape the future from Arkansas.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (9/36) We know the success of our transportation industry is critical to the economic future of AR. To position our state for the future we must act today because the future of supply chain deliveries will be different tomorrow from trucks on our road today. Let‚Äôs keep leading.

name: Gov. Asa Hutchinson
tweet: (6/36) In 1956, the Eisenhower administration laid out a bold plan to change the way Americans moved. The Interstate Highway System connected all parts of America, even previously remote states like Arkansas. This concept was bold at a time when many Americans traveled by train.
